<!-- ═══════════════════════════════ ANALYTICAL GEOMETRY ═══════════════════════════════ -->
<div id="analytic" class="section">
  <div class="sec-header">
    <div class="sec-icon" style="background:rgba(0,201,177,0.15)">📐</div>
    <div>
      <h2>Analytical Geometry</h2>
      <p>Topic 1 · All aspects learnt</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- 1a Distance -->
  <div class="card">
    <div class="card-title">a. Distance Formula <span class="tag">Core</span></div>
    <div class="def-box">
      <div class="def-word">Definition</div>
      The distance formula calculates the straight-line (Euclidean) distance between two points A(x₁;y₁) and B(x₂;y₂) on a Cartesian plane. It is derived from the Theorem of Pythagoras.
    </div>
    <div class="formula-box">
      <div class="label">Formula</div>
      AB = √[(x₂ − x₁)² + (y₂ − y₁)²]
    </div>
    <div class="example">
      <div class="ex-label">Example 1 — Basic distance</div>
      <p>Find the distance between A(2 ; 3) and B(6 ; 7).</p>
      <p class="step">AB = √[(6−2)² + (7−3)²] = √[16 + 16] = √32 = 4√2</p>
      <div class="answer">∴ AB = 4√2 units</div>
    </div>
    <div class="example">
      <div class="ex-label">Example 2 — Find unknown coordinate</div>
      <p>A(1 ; 2) and B(x ; 5). AB = √13. Find x.</p>
      <p class="step">√[(x−1)² + (5−2)²] = √13</p>
      <p class="step">(x−1)² + 9 = 13 → (x−1)² = 4 → x−1 = ±2</p>
      <div class="answer">∴ x = 3 or x = −1</div>
    </div>
    <div class="warn-box">Common mistake: Forgetting to square-root at the end, or confusing (x₂−x₁) with (y₂−y₁).</div>
  </div>

  <!-- 1b Gradient -->
  <div class="card">
    <div class="card-title">b. Gradient Formula <span class="tag">Core</span></div>
    <div class="def-box">
      <div class="def-word">Definition</div>
      The gradient (slope) of a line measures its steepness. It is the ratio of the vertical change (rise) to the horizontal change (run) between two points on the line.
    </div>
    <div class="formula-box">
      <div class="label">Formula</div>
      m = (y₂ − y₁) / (x₂ − x₁)
    </div>
    <ul class="notes">
      <li><strong>Positive gradient:</strong> line slopes upward left → right</li>
      <li><strong>Negative gradient:</strong> line slopes downward left → right</li>
      <li><strong>Zero gradient:</strong> horizontal line (m = 0)</li>
      <li><strong>Undefined gradient:</strong> vertical line (x₂ = x₁)</li>
      <li><strong>Parallel lines:</strong> m₁ = m₂</li>
      <li><strong>Perpendicular lines:</strong> m₁ × m₂ = −1</li>
    </ul>
    <div class="example">
      <div class="ex-label">Example</div>
      <p>Show that A(0;2), B(3;5) and C(−2;−1) are collinear (on the same line).</p>
      <p class="step">m_AB = (5−2)/(3−0) = 3/3 = 1</p>
      <p class="step">m_BC = (−1−5)/(−2−3) = −6/−5 = 6/5... wait let me recheck: m_AC = (−1−2)/(−2−0) = −3/−2 = 3/2</p>
      <p class="step">m_AB = (5−2)/(3−0) = 1; m_AC = (−1−2)/(−2−0) = 3/2. Not collinear here — but the method is: if all gradients between pairs of points are equal, the points are collinear.</p>
      <div class="answer">If m_AB = m_BC = m_AC → points are collinear.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="example">
      <div class="ex-label">Example — Perpendicular</div>
      <p>Line l has gradient 3. What is the gradient of a line perpendicular to l?</p>
      <p class="step">m_perp × 3 = −1 → m_perp = −1/3</p>
      <div class="answer">∴ m_perp = −⅓</div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- 1c Equation of straight line -->
  <div class="card">
    <div class="card-title">c. Equation of a Straight Line <span class="tag">Core</span></div>
    <div class="formula-box">
      <div class="label">Two forms</div>
      Slope-intercept:  y = mx + c<br>
      Point-slope:      y − y₁ = m(x − x₁)
    </div>
    <div class="def-box">
      <div class="def-word">How to find the equation</div>
      You always need: (1) the gradient m, and (2) one point on the line.
    </div>
    <div class="example">
      <div class="ex-label">Example 1</div>
      <p>Find the equation of the line through (2;1) and (4;7).</p>
      <p class="step">m = (7−1)/(4−2) = 6/2 = 3</p>
      <p class="step">y − 1 = 3(x − 2) → y − 1 = 3x − 6</p>
      <div class="answer">∴ y = 3x − 5</div>
    </div>
    <div class="example">
      <div class="ex-label">Example 2 — Perpendicular line</div>
      <p>Find the equation of the line through (1;4) perpendicular to y = 2x + 3.</p>
      <p class="step">Gradient of given line: m = 2 → m_perp = −½</p>
      <p class="step">y − 4 = −½(x − 1) → y = −½x + 4½</p>
      <div class="answer">∴ y = −½x + 4.5</div>
    </div>
    <div class="example">
      <div class="ex-label">Example 3 — Parallel line</div>
      <p>Find the equation of the line parallel to 3x + y = 5 passing through (0; −2).</p>
      <p class="step">y = −3x + 5 → m = −3; parallel means same m</p>
      <p class="step">y = −3x + c; substitute (0;−2): −2 = 0 + c → c = −2</p>
      <div class="answer">∴ y = −3x − 2</div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- 1d Angle of Inclination -->
  <div class="card">
    <div class="card-title">d. Angle of Inclination <span class="tag">Core</span></div>
    <div class="def-box">
      <div class="def-word">Definition</div>
      The angle of inclination (θ) is the angle the line makes with the positive x-axis, measured anti-clockwise. It satisfies 0° ≤ θ &lt; 180°.
    </div>
    <div class="formula-box">
      <div class="label">Formula</div>
      m = tan θ  →  θ = arctan(m)<br>
      If m &lt; 0: θ is obtuse (between 90° and 180°)
    </div>
    <ul class="notes">
      <li>If m > 0 → θ is acute (0° &lt; θ &lt; 90°)</li>
      <li>If m &lt; 0 → θ is obtuse (90° &lt; θ &lt; 180°) — add 180° to calculator answer if negative</li>
      <li>If m = 0 → θ = 0° (horizontal line)</li>
      <li>Vertical line → θ = 90° (undefined m)</li>
    </ul>
    <div class="example">
      <div class="ex-label">Example 1</div>
      <p>Find the angle of inclination of y = 2x + 1.</p>
      <p class="step">m = 2 → tan θ = 2 → θ = arctan(2)</p>
      <div class="answer">∴ θ ≈ 63.43°</div>
    </div>
    <div class="example">
      <div class="ex-label">Example 2 — Negative gradient</div>
      <p>Find θ for the line through (1;4) and (3;−2).</p>
      <p class="step">m = (−2−4)/(3−1) = −6/2 = −3</p>
      <p class="step">tan θ = −3 → calculator gives −71.57°; since θ must be in [0°;180°): θ = 180° − 71.57°</p>
      <div class="answer">∴ θ ≈ 108.43°</div>
    </div>
    <div class="example">
      <div class="ex-label">Example 3 — Angle between two lines</div>
      <p>Lines with inclinations α and β. Find angle between them: use m₁ and m₂ with tan formula or just subtract inclinations.</p>
      <p class="step">The angle φ between two lines: tan φ = |(m₁ − m₂)/(1 + m₁m₂)|</p>
      <div class="answer">Note: This formula is sometimes asked in tougher questions.</div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- 1e Area -->
  <div class="card">
    <div class="card-title">e. Area of Geometrical Shape <span class="tag">Application</span></div>
    <div class="def-box">
      <div class="def-word">Using coordinates to find area</div>
      Combine distance formula (for lengths), the gradient (for perpendicularity / height), and geometry area formulas.
    </div>
    <div class="formula-box">
      <div class="label">Area of Triangle (Coordinate Geometry)</div>
      Area = ½|x₁(y₂−y₃) + x₂(y₃−y₁) + x₃(y₁−y₂)|<br><br>
      Or: Area = ½ × base × height
    </div>
    <div class="example">
      <div class="ex-label">Example</div>
      <p>Find the area of △ABC with A(0;0), B(4;0), C(2;3).</p>
      <p class="step">Using ½ × base × height: base AB = 4 units (along x-axis), height = y-coordinate of C = 3</p>
      <p class="step">Area = ½ × 4 × 3 = 6</p>
      <div class="answer">∴ Area = 6 square units</div>
    </div>
    <div class="example">
      <div class="ex-label">Example 2 — Shoelace Formula</div>
      <p>A(1;2), B(5;2), C(3;6). Find area using shoelace.</p>
      <p class="step">= ½|1(2−6) + 5(6−2) + 3(2−2)|</p>
      <p class="step">= ½|1(−4) + 5(4) + 3(0)| = ½|−4 + 20| = ½ × 16</p>
      <div class="answer">∴ Area = 8 square units</div>
    </div>
    <div class="warn-box">Exam tip: When they give 4 points (quadrilateral), split it into 2 triangles or use the shoelace formula for polygons.</div>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- ═══════════════════════════════ TRIGONOMETRY ═══════════════════════════════ -->
<div id="trig" class="section">
  <div class="sec-header">
    <div class="sec-icon" style="background:rgba(255,107,157,0.15)">📐</div>
    <div>
      <h2>Trigonometry</h2>
      <p>Topic 2 · All aspects (excluding trig functions/graphs)</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- 2a Diagrams and Pythagoras -->
  <div class="card">
    <div class="card-title">a. Diagrams & Pythagoras Theorem <span class="tag">Core</span></div>
    <div class="def-box">
      <div class="def-word">CAST Diagram</div>
      Shows which trig ratios are POSITIVE in each quadrant:<br>
      Quadrant 1 (0°–90°): ALL positive<br>
      Quadrant 2 (90°–180°): Sine positive<br>
      Quadrant 3 (180°–270°): Tan positive<br>
      Quadrant 4 (270°–360°): Cos positive
    </div>
    <div class="formula-box">
      <div class="label">Basic Trig Ratios (right triangle)</div>
      sin θ = opposite/hypotenuse = y/r<br>
      cos θ = adjacent/hypotenuse = x/r<br>
      tan θ = opposite/adjacent = y/x<br><br>
      Pythagoras: r² = x² + y²
    </div>
    <div class="example">
      <div class="ex-label">Example 1</div>
      <p>If sin θ = 3/5 and θ is in Q1, find cos θ and tan θ without a calculator.</p>
      <p class="step">y = 3, r = 5 → x = √(25−9) = √16 = 4</p>
      <p class="step">cos θ = 4/5; tan θ = 3/4</p>
      <div class="answer">∴ cos θ = 4/5; tan θ = ¾</div>
    </div>
    <div class="example">
      <div class="ex-label">Example 2 — Second Quadrant</div>
      <p>If cos θ = −12/13 and θ ∈ (90°;180°), find sin θ and tan θ.</p>
      <p class="step">Q2: cos is negative, sin is positive; x = −12, r = 13</p>
      <p class="step">y = √(169−144) = √25 = 5</p>
      <p class="step">sin θ = 5/13; tan θ = y/x = 5/(−12) = −5/12</p>
      <div class="answer">∴ sin θ = 5/13; tan θ = −5/12</div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- 2b Reductions -->
  <div class="card">
    <div class="card-title">b. Reduction Formulae <span class="tag">Core</span></div>
    <div class="def-box">
      <div class="def-word">Definition</div>
      Reduction formulae let us write trig ratios of any angle in terms of acute angles (reference angles). We use the CAST rule and co-ratios together.
    </div>
    <table>
      <tr><th>Form</th><th>sin</th><th>cos</th><th>tan</th></tr>
      <tr><td>180° − θ (Q2)</td><td>sin θ</td><td>−cos θ</td><td>−tan θ</td></tr>
      <tr><td>180° + θ (Q3)</td><td>−sin θ</td><td>−cos θ</td><td>tan θ</td></tr>
      <tr><td>360° − θ (Q4)</td><td>−sin θ</td><td>cos θ</td><td>−tan θ</td></tr>
      <tr><td>−θ (Q4)</td><td>−sin θ</td><td>cos θ</td><td>−tan θ</td></tr>
    </table>
    <div class="formula-box">
      <div class="label">Memory trick</div>
      "180° ± θ" → the ratio NAME STAYS THE SAME (sign changes by CAST)<br>
      "90° ± θ" → the ratio CHANGES (sin↔cos, co-function)
    </div>
    <div class="example">
      <div class="ex-label">Example — Simplify</div>
      <p>Simplify: sin(180°−θ) · cos(360°−θ) / tan(180°+θ)</p>
      <p class="step">sin(180°−θ) = sin θ</p>
      <p class="step">cos(360°−θ) = cos θ</p>
      <p class="step">tan(180°+θ) = tan θ</p>
      <p class="step">= (sin θ · cos θ) / tan θ = sin θ · cos θ · (cos θ/sin θ)</p>
      <div class="answer">∴ = cos²θ</div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- 2c Co-ratios -->
  <div class="card">
    <div class="card-title">c. Co-ratios (Complementary Angles) <span class="tag">Core</span></div>
    <div class="def-box">
      <div class="def-word">Definition</div>
      Co-ratios connect trig functions of complementary angles. When the angle is (90° − θ) or (90° + θ), the function swaps to its co-function.
    </div>
    <table>
      <tr><th>Rule</th><th>Result</th></tr>
      <tr><td>sin(90° − θ)</td><td>cos θ</td></tr>
      <tr><td>cos(90° − θ)</td><td>sin θ</td></tr>
      <tr><td>sin(90° + θ)</td><td>cos θ</td></tr>
      <tr><td>cos(90° + θ)</td><td>−sin θ</td></tr>
      <tr><td>tan(90° − θ)</td><td>1/tan θ = cot θ</td></tr>
    </table>
    <div class="example">
      <div class="ex-label">Example</div>
      <p>Simplify: sin(90° − θ) + cos(90° + θ) − sin(−θ)</p>
      <p class="step">= cos θ + (−sin θ) − (−sin θ)</p>
      <p class="step">= cos θ − sin θ + sin θ</p>
      <div class="answer">∴ = cos θ</div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- 2d Identities -->
  <div class="card">
    <div class="card-title">d. Trigonometric Identities <span class="tag">High Mark</span></div>
    <div class="formula-box">
      <div class="label">Fundamental Identities</div>
      (1) sin²θ + cos²θ = 1<br>
      (2) tan θ = sin θ / cos θ<br>
      (3) From (1): sin²θ = 1 − cos²θ and cos²θ = 1 − sin²θ
    </div>
    <div class="def-box">
      <div class="def-word">Proving Identities — Rules</div>
      ① Start with the MORE complicated side.<br>
      ② Work on ONE side only (unless doing LHS = ... = RHS).<br>
      ③ Convert everything to sin and cos.<br>
      ④ Look for Pythagorean substitution: sin²θ + cos²θ = 1.<br>
      ⑤ Factorize where possible.
    </div>
    <div class="example">
      <div class="ex-label">Proof 1 — Standard</div>
      <p>Prove: (1 − cos²θ)/sin θ = sin θ</p>
      <p class="step">LHS = sin²θ/sin θ = sin θ = RHS ✓</p>
      <div class="answer">Identity proved.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="example">
      <div class="ex-label">Proof 2 — Harder</div>
      <p>Prove: (sin θ + cos θ)² − 1 = 2 sin θ cos θ</p>
      <p class="step">LHS = sin²θ + 2sinθcosθ + cos²θ − 1</p>
      <p class="step">= (sin²θ + cos²θ) + 2sinθcosθ − 1</p>
      <p class="step">= 1 + 2sinθcosθ − 1 = 2sinθcosθ = RHS ✓</p>
      <div class="answer">Identity proved.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="example">
      <div class="ex-label">Proof 3 — With fractions</div>
      <p>Prove: 1/(1+sinθ) + 1/(1−sinθ) = 2/cos²θ</p>
      <p class="step">LHS = [(1−sinθ) + (1+sinθ)] / [(1+sinθ)(1−sinθ)]</p>
      <p class="step">= 2 / (1 − sin²θ) = 2/cos²θ = RHS ✓</p>
      <div class="answer">Identity proved.</div>
    </div>
    <hr class="divider">
    <p style="font-size:14px;margin-bottom:14px;"><strong class="hl-gold">Simplification of Trig Expressions</strong></p>
    <div class="example">
      <div class="ex-label">Example</div>
      <p>Simplify: sin(180°+θ)·tan(360°−θ) / cos(−θ)·sin(90°−θ)</p>
      <p class="step">= (−sinθ)(−tanθ) / (cosθ)(cosθ)</p>
      <p class="step">= sinθ·tanθ / cos²θ = sinθ·(sinθ/cosθ)/cos²θ</p>
      <p class="step">= sin²θ / cos³θ</p>
      <div class="answer">∴ = sin²θ / cos³θ</div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- 2e General Solutions -->
  <div class="card">
    <div class="card-title">e. General Solutions <span class="tag">Core</span></div>
    <div class="def-box">
      <div class="def-word">Definition</div>
      Because trig functions are periodic, equations have infinitely many solutions. The general solution gives ALL solutions using the period of the function. We add n × period (n ∈ ℤ).
    </div>
    <div class="formula-box">
      <div class="label">General Solution Rules</div>
      sin θ = k → θ = arcsin(k) + 360°n  OR  θ = 180° − arcsin(k) + 360°n<br>
      cos θ = k → θ = ±arccos(k) + 360°n<br>
      tan θ = k → θ = arctan(k) + 180°n<br><br>
      where n ∈ ℤ (integer)
    </div>
    <div class="example">
      <div class="ex-label">Example 1 — sin equation</div>
      <p>Solve: sin θ = 0.5 (general solution)</p>
      <p class="step">Reference angle = arcsin(0.5) = 30°</p>
      <p class="step">sin is positive in Q1 and Q2</p>
      <p class="step">θ = 30° + 360°n  or  θ = 150° + 360°n, n ∈ ℤ</p>
      <div class="answer">∴ θ = 30° + 360°n or θ = 150° + 360°n</div>
    </div>
    <div class="example">
      <div class="ex-label">Example 2 — cos equation</div>
      <p>Solve: cos θ = −½</p>
      <p class="step">Reference = arccos(½) = 60°; cos is negative in Q2 and Q3</p>
      <p class="step">θ = 180° − 60° + 360°n = 120° + 360°n</p>
      <p class="step">θ = 180° + 60° + 360°n = 240° + 360°n</p>
      <p class="step">Using general formula: θ = ±120° + 360°n</p>
      <div class="answer">∴ θ = 120° + 360°n or θ = −120° + 360°n</div>
    </div>
    <div class="example">
      <div class="ex-label">Example 3 — tan equation</div>
      <p>Solve: tan θ = √3</p>
      <p class="step">Reference = arctan(√3) = 60°</p>
      <div class="answer">∴ θ = 60° + 180°n, n ∈ ℤ</div>
    </div>
    <div class="example">
      <div class="ex-label">Example 4 — Restricted domain</div>
      <p>Solve 2cos θ − 1 = 0 for θ ∈ [−180°; 360°]</p>
      <p class="step">cos θ = ½ → θ = ±60° + 360°n</p>
      <p class="step">n=0: θ = 60° or θ = −60°</p>
      <p class="step">n=1: θ = 60°+360° = 420° (too big); θ = −60°+360° = 300°</p>
      <p class="step">n=−1: θ = 60°−360° = −300° (too small); θ = −60°−360° = −420° (too small)</p>
      <div class="answer">∴ θ ∈ {−60°; 60°; 300°}</div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- ═══════════════════════════════ EUCLIDEAN GEOMETRY ═══════════════════════════════ -->
<div id="euclid" class="section">
  <div class="sec-header">
    <div class="sec-icon" style="background:rgba(91,156,246,0.15)">🔷</div>
    <div>
      <h2>Euclidean Geometry</h2>
      <p>Topic 3 · Grade 11 ATP Theorems</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="card">
    <div class="card-title">Grade 11 Euclidean Geometry Theorems <span class="tag">Must Know</span></div>
    <div class="warn-box">You must be able to PROVE these theorems AND apply them. State the theorem/reason clearly in each step.</div>

    <table>
      <tr><th>#</th><th>Theorem</th><th>Key Statement</th></tr>
      <tr><td>T1</td><td>Line from centre to midpoint</td><td>The line from the centre of a circle to the midpoint of a chord is perpendicular to the chord.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>T2</td><td>Perpendicular from centre</td><td>The perpendicular from the centre of a circle to a chord bisects the chord.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>T3</td><td>Angle at centre = 2 × inscribed</td><td>The angle subtended by an arc at the centre is double the angle subtended at the circumference.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>T4</td><td>Angles in same segment</td><td>Angles subtended by the same arc (chord) in the same segment are equal.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>T5</td><td>Angle in semicircle = 90°</td><td>The angle in a semicircle is 90° (angle subtended by diameter at circumference).</td></tr>
      <tr><td>T6</td><td>Opposite angles of cyclic quad</td><td>Opposite angles of a cyclic quadrilateral are supplementary (add up to 180°).</td></tr>
      <tr><td>T7</td><td>Exterior angle of cyclic quad</td><td>The exterior angle of a cyclic quadrilateral equals the interior opposite angle.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>T8</td><td>Tangent-radius</td><td>The tangent to a circle is perpendicular to the radius at the point of tangency.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>T9</td><td>Tangent from external point</td><td>Tangent segments from an external point are equal in length.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>T10</td><td>Tan-chord angle</td><td>The angle between a tangent and a chord equals the inscribed angle on the opposite side (tan-chord = angle in alt. segment).</td></tr>
    </table>
  </div>

  <div class="card">
    <div class="card-title">a. Proof of Theorems — Key Proofs</div>
    <div class="example">
      <div class="ex-label">Proof: Angle at Centre = 2 × Angle at Circumference</div>
      <p><strong>Given:</strong> Circle with centre O. Arc BC subtends ∠BOC at centre and ∠BAC at A on circumference.</p>
      <p><strong>To prove:</strong> ∠BOC = 2∠BAC</p>
      <p class="step">Construction: Draw AO and extend to D.</p>
      <p class="step">In △AOB: OA = OB (radii) → △AOB is isosceles</p>
      <p class="step">∴ ∠OAB = ∠OBA (base angles equal)</p>
      <p class="step">Ext angle: ∠BOD = ∠OAB + ∠OBA = 2∠OAB</p>
      <p class="step">Similarly in △AOC: ∠COD = 2∠OAC</p>
      <p class="step">∴ ∠BOC = ∠BOD + ∠COD = 2∠OAB + 2∠OAC = 2∠BAC ✓</p>
      <div class="answer">∠BOC = 2∠BAC (angle at centre = 2 × angle at circumference)</div>
    </div>
    <div class="example">
      <div class="ex-label">Proof: Opposite Angles of Cyclic Quad = 180°</div>
      <p><strong>Given:</strong> Cyclic quad ABCD.</p>
      <p><strong>To prove:</strong> ∠A + ∠C = 180°</p>
      <p class="step">Arc BCD subtends reflex ∠BOD at centre = 2∠A (angle at centre)</p>
      <p class="step">Arc BAD subtends ∠BOD (minor) at centre = 2∠C</p>
      <p class="step">Reflex ∠BOD + ∠BOD = 360° (angles around point)</p>
      <p class="step">∴ 2∠A + 2∠C = 360° → ∠A + ∠C = 180° ✓</p>
      <div class="answer">Opposite angles of a cyclic quadrilateral are supplementary.</div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="card">
    <div class="card-title">b. Application of Theorems <span class="tag">Application</span></div>
    <div class="def-box">
      <div class="def-word">Approach to Solving Euclidean Geometry Questions</div>
      Step 1: Read question and mark all given info on diagram.<br>
      Step 2: Identify which theorem applies (look for equal radii, chords, arcs).<br>
      Step 3: Write each statement with a reason.<br>
      Step 4: Work towards what is required.
    </div>
    <div class="example">
      <div class="ex-label">Example 1</div>
      <p>O is the centre. ∠AOB = 110°. Find ∠ACB where C is on the major arc.</p>
      <p class="step">∠AOB = 2∠ACB (angle at centre = 2 × angle at circumference, same arc AB)</p>
      <p class="step">But ∠ACB is in major arc, so we use reflex ∠AOB = 360° − 110° = 250°</p>
      <p class="step">∠ACB = 250°/2 = 125°</p>
      <div class="answer">∴ ∠ACB = 125°</div>
    </div>
    <div class="example">
      <div class="ex-label">Example 2 — Cyclic Quad</div>
      <p>ABCD is a cyclic quad. ∠A = 3x and ∠C = x + 40°. Find x.</p>
      <p class="step">∠A + ∠C = 180° (opp angles cyclic quad)</p>
      <p class="step">3x + x + 40° = 180° → 4x = 140° → x = 35°</p>
      <div class="answer">∴ x = 35°; ∠A = 105°; ∠C = 75°</div>
    </div>
    <div class="example">
      <div class="ex-label">Example 3 — Tangent-Chord</div>
      <p>TB is a tangent at B. Chord BC. ∠TBC = 42°. Find the angle in the alternate segment.</p>
      <p class="step">By tan-chord theorem: angle in alternate segment = ∠TBC = 42°</p>
      <div class="answer">∴ ∠BAC = 42° (tan-chord = angle in alternate segment)</div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="card">
    <div class="card-title">🔑 Euclidean Geometry Reasons (Abbreviations)</div>
    <table>
      <tr><th>Theorem</th><th>How to write the reason</th></tr>
      <tr><td>Angle at centre</td><td>∠ at centre = 2 × ∠ at circumference</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Angles in same segment</td><td>∠s in same segment</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Angle in semicircle</td><td>∠ in semicircle = 90°</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Opp angles cyclic quad</td><td>opp ∠s cyclic quad (or: ABCD is a cyclic quad)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Exterior angle cyclic quad</td><td>ext ∠ cyclic quad</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Tangent-radius</td><td>tan ⊥ radius</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Tangent from external point</td><td>tans from common ext point</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Tan-chord angle</td><td>tan-chord theorem (∠ in alt. segment)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Equal radii</td><td>radii</td></tr>
    </table>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- ═══════════════════════════════ SINE & COSINE ═══════════════════════════════ -->
<div id="sine-cosine" class="section">
  <div class="sec-header">
    <div class="sec-icon" style="background:rgba(74,222,128,0.15)">📏</div>
    <div>
      <h2>Sine & Cosine Rules</h2>
      <p>Topic 4 · Proofs, application, area rule</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="card">
    <div class="card-title">a. Proof of the Rules</div>
    <div class="formula-box">
      <div class="label">Sine Rule</div>
      a/sin A = b/sin B = c/sin C
    </div>
    <div class="example">
      <div class="ex-label">Proof of Sine Rule</div>
      <p>In △ABC, draw altitude h from B to AC.</p>
      <p class="step">In △ABD: sin A = h/c → h = c·sin A</p>
      <p class="step">In △BCD: sin C = h/a → h = a·sin C</p>
      <p class="step">∴ c·sin A = a·sin C → a/sin A = c/sin C ✓</p>
      <p class="step">Similarly draw another altitude to prove b/sin B = a/sin A</p>
      <div class="answer">∴ a/sin A = b/sin B = c/sin C (Sine Rule proven)</div>
    </div>
    <div class="formula-box">
      <div class="label">Cosine Rule</div>
      a² = b² + c² − 2bc·cos A<br>
      (Also: b² = a² + c² − 2ac·cos B)<br>
      (Also: c² = a² + b² − 2ab·cos C)
    </div>
    <div class="example">
      <div class="ex-label">Proof of Cosine Rule</div>
      <p>In △ABC, drop perpendicular from A to BC at D. Let BD = x.</p>
      <p class="step">In △ABD: x = c·cos B; AD = c·sin B</p>
      <p class="step">In △ACD: b² = AD² + DC² = (c·sinB)² + (a−c·cosB)²</p>
      <p class="step">= c²sin²B + a² − 2ac·cosB + c²cos²B</p>
      <p class="step">= c²(sin²B + cos²B) + a² − 2ac·cosB</p>
      <p class="step">= c² + a² − 2ac·cosB ✓ (this gives b² = a² + c² − 2ac·cosB)</p>
      <div class="answer">Cosine Rule proved: a² = b² + c² − 2bc·cos A</div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="card">
    <div class="card-title">b. Applying the Rules <span class="tag">Application</span></div>
    <div class="def-box">
      <div class="def-word">When to use which rule</div>
      <strong>Use Sine Rule</strong> when you know: AAS, ASA, or SSA (ambiguous case)<br>
      <strong>Use Cosine Rule</strong> when you know: SAS or SSS
    </div>
    <div class="example">
      <div class="ex-label">Example 1 — Sine Rule (finding a side)</div>
      <p>In △ABC: ∠A = 50°, ∠B = 70°, a = 8. Find b.</p>
      <p class="step">b/sin B = a/sin A → b/sin70° = 8/sin50°</p>
      <p class="step">b = 8·sin70°/sin50° = 8 × 0.9397/0.7660</p>
      <div class="answer">∴ b ≈ 9.81 units</div>
    </div>
    <div class="example">
      <div class="ex-label">Example 2 — Cosine Rule (finding a side)</div>
      <p>In △ABC: b = 7, c = 5, ∠A = 60°. Find a.</p>
      <p class="step">a² = b² + c² − 2bc·cosA = 49 + 25 − 2(7)(5)cos60°</p>
      <p class="step">= 74 − 70(0.5) = 74 − 35 = 39</p>
      <div class="answer">∴ a = √39 ≈ 6.24</div>
    </div>
    <div class="example">
      <div class="ex-label">Example 3 — Cosine Rule (finding an angle)</div>
      <p>In △ABC: a = 5, b = 7, c = 8. Find ∠A.</p>
      <p class="step">cos A = (b² + c² − a²)/(2bc) = (49 + 64 − 25)/(2×7×8) = 88/112 = 11/14</p>
      <p class="step">∠A = arccos(11/14)</p>
      <div class="answer">∴ ∠A ≈ 38.21°</div>
    </div>
    <div class="example">
      <div class="ex-label">Example 4 — Mixed problem with circles</div>
      <p>Two radii OA = OB = 10cm, ∠AOB = 80°. Find chord AB.</p>
      <p class="step">AB² = OA² + OB² − 2·OA·OB·cos(∠AOB)</p>
      <p class="step">= 100 + 100 − 200·cos80° = 200 − 200(0.1736) = 200 − 34.73 = 165.27</p>
      <div class="answer">∴ AB ≈ 12.86 cm</div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="card">
    <div class="card-title">c. Area Rule <span class="tag">Core</span></div>
    <div class="formula-box">
      <div class="label">Area Rule</div>
      Area △ABC = ½·b·c·sin A<br>
      Area △ABC = ½·a·c·sin B<br>
      Area △ABC = ½·a·b·sin C<br><br>
      (Use ANY two sides and the INCLUDED angle)
    </div>
    <div class="example">
      <div class="ex-label">Example 1</div>
      <p>b = 6, c = 9, ∠A = 35°. Find the area of △ABC.</p>
      <p class="step">Area = ½ × 6 × 9 × sin35° = 27 × 0.5736</p>
      <div class="answer">∴ Area ≈ 15.49 cm²</div>
    </div>
    <div class="example">
      <div class="ex-label">Example 2 — Find unknown side from area</div>
      <p>Area of △PQR = 24 cm². PQ = 8 cm, ∠P = 40°. Find PR.</p>
      <p class="step">24 = ½ × 8 × PR × sin40°</p>
      <p class="step">24 = 4 × PR × 0.6428 → PR = 24/(4 × 0.6428)</p>
      <div class="answer">∴ PR ≈ 9.33 cm</div>
    </div>
    <div class="example">
      <div class="ex-label">Example 3 — Compound shape</div>
      <p>ABCD is a quadrilateral with diagonal AC = 15. ∠ABC = 55°, AB = 10; ∠ACD = 40°, CD = 12. Find total area.</p>
      <p class="step">Area △ABC = ½ × AB × AC × sin(∠BAC) ... use cosine rule first for ∠BAC</p>
      <p class="step">Or split into 2 triangles and use area rule on each.</p>
      <div class="answer">Always split complex shapes into triangles and apply the area rule.</div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

